cd onnxruntime
build.bat --config RelWithDebInfo --build_wheel

i meant running it from the build.bat script.

anyway, i think python setup.py bdist_wheel needs to be run in the same directory where your onnxruntime folder resides (that you screenshot'd above)
i.e. onnxruntime\build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo

my build output shows this:
2019-07-22 09:28:53,009 Build [DEBUG] - Running subprocess in 'D:\onnxruntime\build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo'
['C:\Users\jywu\AppData\Local\Continuum\Anaconda3\python.exe', 'D:\onnxruntime\setup.py', 'bdist_wheel']

Thanks @jywu-msft , I got it now. So, there are two steps -

1> `build.bat --config RelWithDebInfo --build_wheel`
2> `cd build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo & python 'D:\onnxruntime\setup.py' bdist_wheel`

> Thanks @jywu-msft , I got it now. So, there are two steps -
> 
> 1> `build.bat --config RelWithDebInfo --build_wheel`
> 2> `cd build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo & python 'D:\onnxruntime\setup.py' bdist_wheel`

not quite. the build.bat script should internally call python setup.py bdist_wheel in the appropriate directory when you pass the --build_wheel option.
this is why i was asking for the relevant part of the output of build.bat to see what happened.

> Thanks @jywu-msft , I got it now. So, there are two steps -
> 
> 1> `build.bat --config RelWithDebInfo --build_wheel`
> 2> `cd build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo & python 'D:\onnxruntime\setup.py' bdist_wheel`

@priyanka1023 thank you so much for posting this solution.  I agree with @jywu-msft that the build script should internally call the `pythong setup.py bdist_wheel`.  However, till that is fixed I was able to generate and use the wheel file.
In my case --skip_tests helped. Without --skip_tests the wheel wasn't produced.
